{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"309452ee-efc4-425c-8875-f520d230663f","content":"`SafeAreaEdges` isn't a built-in `ContentPage` property in .NET MAUI. You likely need a combination of platform-specific settings:\n\n**1. iOS — disable safe area insets:**\n```xml\n<ContentPage xmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\n             ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\"\n             Padding=\"0\">\n```\n\n**2. Android — make system bars transparent:**\n\nIn your `MainActivity.cs` or platform startup, ensure the window draws edge-to-edge:\n\n```csharp\n#if ANDROID\nWindow.SetStatusBarColor(Android.Graphics.Color.Transparent);\nWindow.SetNavigationBarColor(Android.Graphics.Color.Transparent);\n#endif\n```\n\n> In .NET 10 targeting Android 15+, edge-to-edge is enforced by default, but the system bar backgrounds may still be opaque unless you explicitly set them transparent.\n\n**3. Make sure the Image fills the space:**\n```xml\n<Image Source=\"photo.jpg\"\n       Aspect=\"AspectFill\"\n       HorizontalOptions=\"Fill\"\n       VerticalOptions=\"Fill\" />\n```\n\n**4. Check for stray padding/margin** on the `ContentPage`, `Shell`, or any wrapping layout — set `Padding=\"0\"` and `Margin=\"0\"` as needed.\n\nThe most common culprit is the missing `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\"` on iOS and non-transparent system bars on Android.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c8668120-1d7a-4507-9418-21120b0c5c27","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about making an image go edge-to-edge in a .NET MAUI app, going behind the status bar and navigation bar. They've tried `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` on the ContentPage but the image still has padding.\n\nThis is a common .NET MAUI question. Let me think about what they need:\n\n1. `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` is not a standard .NET MAUI API on ContentPage. They might be confusing it with something else.\n\n2. To go edge-to-edge in .NET MAUI, you typically need to:\n   - On **Android**: Use `Window.DecorFitsSystemWindows = false` or set the status bar/navigation bar to transparent, or use the `Edge2Edge` APIs available in newer .NET MAUI versions.\n   - On **iOS**: The safe area insets need to be ignored using the `UseSafeArea` platform-specific property set to false through XAML markup.\n\nFor Android, newer versions of .NET MAUI have built-in edge-to-edge support, though the exact implementation depends on the .NET version being used.\n\nI'm realizing that `SafeAreaEdges` isn't actually a standard .NET MAUI property—the user might be thinking of a different framework or a custom implementation. The actual approach for going edge-to-edge involves platform-specific configurations rather than a single unified property. The Image control needs `Aspect=\"AspectFill\"` to properly fill the screen, and I should clarify that `SafeAreaEdges` isn't a standard .NET MAUI property—it might be from the Community Toolkit or a custom implementation. For a practical solution, I'd recommend setting `Padding=\"0\"` on the page and using the platform-specific approaches: `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\"` for iOS and configuring transparent system bars on Android for true edge-to-edge display.","outputTokens":1336,"requestId":"D44A:298C73:1D40E74:20C0110:6A07BF86"},"id":"85ef95a6-5186-4b41-8634-a641cdd7783c","timestamp":"2026-05-16T00:51:44.655Z","parentId":"afa1c083-a4e3-49b3-9af5-32c91e4ae36e"}
